<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-05-25T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-05-25T08:00:00-05:00" n="156" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d156">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Manchuria/1102: Telegram (part
                            air)</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-05-25T14:00:00+01:00">May 25, 1934—2
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 26—8:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>95. Japanese Consul General here informs me that he has received official
                            notification from his Government of Salvador’s recognition of
                            “Manchukuo”. He states that he understands that thus far this is the
                            only act of any Government which Tokyo construes as constituting formal
                            recognition (Consulate’s 858 Political, March 28,<note n="27" xml:id="d156fn27">Not printed.</note> page 5).</p>
                        <p>It may be noted incidentally that Salvador was not represented in the
                            extraordinary Assembly which on February 24, 1933, voted on the
                            nonrecognition recommendations.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>